		<tr>
			<td>
				<p style="font-size: 12px;font-style: italic;">
					Coffee beans dry in the sun at a processing plant in rural Chiapas, Mexico.&nbsp;<em>(Photo by Rebecca E. Rollins/Partners In Health)</em></p>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>
<h3>
	<strong>A problem solver</strong></h3>
<p>
	Mazariegos began working with PIH when Mac&iacute;as was halfway through her service year. She had no way of knowing the driver would become like her &ldquo;right arm&rdquo; for two years as they built Right to Health Care from the ground up.</p>
<p>
	It all started with Mac&iacute;as having what she calls a &ldquo;tumor week.&rdquo; Patients from miles around flowed through her small clinic in Honduras, Chiapas, almost everyone with an inexplicable mass growing somewhere in their bodies. Many had been living with health problems for months, even years, but never had had access to a doctor like Mac&iacute;as. She could do little beyond refer them to specialized care in a hospital hours away by car, knowing that few&mdash;if any&mdash;would follow up. Most couldn&rsquo;t afford the trip. And even if they could, they weren&rsquo;t accustomed to navigating the Mexican health care system, and were often discriminated against when they did.</p>
<p>
	Frustrated, she talked to Flores and Arrieta to figure out a way to get patients the specialized care they needed. From those talks sparked Right to Health Care, of which Mac&iacute;as was the founding director. Mazariegos became her constant sidekick.</p>
<p>
	After she finished her service year, Mac&iacute;as worked with Mazariegos for two years to forge paths through the complex, and sometimes confusing, Mexican health care system. Each patient presented a new problem to solve. One day, they focused on getting chemotherapy for a breast cancer patient. The next day they tracked down a plastic surgeon for a woman with a debilitating physical deformity. Over time, they developed solid connections with hospital staff, nurses, social workers, and specialists in several cities in and around Chiapas who helped usher patients through the system.</p>
<p>
	Mazariegos was key in forging these relationships. &ldquo;Without him, this program would not have been possible at all,&rdquo; Mac&iacute;as says. &nbsp;</p>
<h3>
	<strong>A tireless advocate</strong></h3>
<p>
	Patients rely on him as well. As part of the Right to Health Care team, Mazariegos arrives at their door before dawn to drive to the closest hospital in Tuxtla Guti&eacute;rrez, the capital of Chiapas. Along the three-hour drive, they chat and tell stories to pass the time. Sometimes ghost stories slip into the mix. (His colleagues say he has an impressive collection.) Once at the hospital, he goes along to morning and afternoon appointments to ensure doctors are offering patients the best options for care. &nbsp;</p>
<p>
	&ldquo;Mo&iacute; has an impressive warmth and treats patients like family,&rdquo; Espinosa says. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really clear in how he acts around them. If one of them becomes seriously ill, he worries a lot.&rdquo;</p>
<p>
	Mazariegos works tirelessly and is &ldquo;on call&rdquo; even when he&rsquo;s off duty. People regularly swing by his in-laws&rsquo; or his family&rsquo;s home to ask for help, because they know he has access to good, local doctors. They say they try, but can&rsquo;t, get care in the Jaltenango hospital. They tell him they need to travel to Tuxtla, Villa Flores, or Tapachula for specialized care, but have no way of getting there. And they ask if he&rsquo;ll come along for appointments, because they feel lost in the system.</p>
<p>
	Sometimes, he says, they simply ask: &ldquo;&rsquo;What is it I have to do so that PIH doctors in nearby communities can see me?&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>
	That&rsquo;s when he used to turn to Mac&iacute;as, and now Espinosa, to plead their cases. &ldquo;&rsquo;We need to put this patient on the list,&rsquo;&rdquo; Mac&iacute;as remembers him saying about patients with complex medical issues. &ldquo;Mo&iacute; has a huge heart.&rdquo;</p>
<p>
	Mazariegos is too humble to acknowledge the major role he plays within the Chiapas team. He does know, however, that he loves his job, which he defined simply as &ldquo;helping without expecting anything in return.&rdquo;</p>
<h3>
	<strong>A constant companion</strong></h3>
<p>
	Espinosa will never forget the time when, as a <em>pasante</em> in Laguna del Cofre, she relied on Mazariegos to get through the most difficult case she&rsquo;d ever experienced. A woman who was developmentally disabled had had six children, almost all of whom had either died or been taken away from her. Only one daughter remained. The girl was clearly suffering and severely malnourished.</p>
<p>
	It was Mazariegos, Espinosa says, who tactfully removed all roadblocks once again. He spoke to local authorities about the family&rsquo;s case to encourage them to act. He visited the mother to explain how giving her child up for foster care was the right thing to do. He found extended family to adopt the young girl. And he was part of the team that got the mother counseling.</p>
<p>
	&nbsp;&ldquo;It was a very difficult, very hard situation that I was not prepared to live through,&rdquo; Espinosa says. She distinctly remembers the two-hour drive from Laguna to Jaltenango the day they brought the child to live with her extended family. She cried the entire route as Mazariegos drove, silent and calm, beside her. Every now and then, she says, &ldquo;Mo&iacute; would look at me and say, &lsquo;<em>Ya, ya, est&aacute; bien</em>.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>
	&ldquo;&rsquo;There, there, it&rsquo;s okay.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p style="font-size: 12px;font-style: italic;">
	<em>In the video below, Mazariegos drives the last stretch of a winding road to a public clinic in Reforma, the community closest to PIH headquarters in Jaltenango, Chiapas.</em></p>
<div id="videoContainer">
	<video class="video-js vjs-default-skin" data-setup="{}" controls="" muted="">
