<item>
      <title>2015: The Year in Quotes</title>
      <link>http://www.pih.org/blog/2015-the-year-in-quotes</link>
      <guid>http://www.pih.org/blog/2015-the-year-in-quotes</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[<div><figure class="bp-header-photo" style="margin-left:0;width:100%;max-width:600px;"><img title="blog photo" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/Mexico_0815_SoledadLuzCommunity_CAvila_010-web01.jpg/@mx_600" style="width:100%;max-width:600px;display:block;"><br><small><figcaption><div class="photo-credit">Photo by Cecille Joan Avila/Partners In Health</div>Partners In Health works in 10 communities throughout rural Chiapas, Mexico.</figcaption></small></figure></div><br><p>
	It&rsquo;s been a busy year, and Partners In Health has had many stories to tell. We helped quash the Ebola epidemic in West Africa, treated multidrug-resistant tuberculosis in Russia, made house calls in Mexico and Malawi, and trained the next generation of clinicians in Haiti and Rwanda. Here&rsquo;s a snapshot of some of the year&#39;s best, and most trying, moments.</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/navajo-nation"><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll clean house, chop wood, haul coal</em>&nbsp;<em>if I have to.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Betty J. John,&nbsp;a PIH&nbsp;community health representative in&nbsp;the Navajo&nbsp;Nation &nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/cholera-vaccine-succeeds-in-haiti-louise-ivers-lancet"><em>&ldquo;When you see people dying, you want to do everything you can.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Dr. Louise C.&nbsp;Ivers, PIH&rsquo;s senior health and policy adviser, on why she&nbsp;pressed for an ambitious,&nbsp;and controversial,&nbsp;cholera vaccine program in Haiti&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/daily-life-in-an-ebola-treatment-unit"><em>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s the right thing to do.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Karin&nbsp;Huster, on&nbsp;why she decided to volunteer for PIH as a nurse in&nbsp;an Ebola Treatment Unit in Sierra Leone&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/rwanda-nears-millennium-development-goals"><em>&ldquo;In the 30 years that I&#39;ve been involved in the provision of health care services to the poor and marginalized, I can think of no more dramatic example of a turnaround than that achieved in Rwanda.&rdquo; </em></a><br />
	PIH&nbsp;Co-founder Dr. Paul Farmer&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/pih-mexico-expands-to-two-new-sites-in-chiapas"><em>&ldquo;The truth is that in most of the places that we work, we are either the first doctors or the first functional doctors.&rdquo; </em></a><br />
	Dr. Hugo Flores, PIH&rsquo;s&nbsp;executive director in Mexico &nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/views-from-the-field-ebola-sierra-leone">&ldquo;I asked them, &lsquo;Do you believe in God?&rsquo; One said, &lsquo;I do believe in God. I just believe that Satan is stronger.&#39; And I had to agree. I don&rsquo;t know how anyone can deserve this&mdash;war and then Ebola, torture on torture.&rdquo;</a><br />
	Dr. Luanne Freer, a PIH volunteer recalling a conversation with Sierra Leonean colleagues working with her in an Ebola Treatment Unit</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/conjoined-twin-sisters-successfully-separated-in-haiti"><em>&ldquo;The guarantee I can give you</em>&nbsp;<em>is that we&#39;re going to look for help for you so that we can keep these babies alive.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Dr. Christophe&nbsp;Milien,&nbsp;PIH&rsquo;s&nbsp;director of obstetrics and gynecology at University Hospital in Mirebalais, Haiti, speaking to his patient who was pregnant with triplets, two of whom were conjoined at the abdomen</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/back-for-good-return-clinicians-west-africa"><em>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m basically leaving the best job in the world for the best job in the world.&rdquo; </em></a><br />
	Devin Platt, who quit his&nbsp;position&nbsp;as a nurse in Oregon&nbsp;to work for PIH at a&nbsp;hospital in Sierra Leone</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/liberias-new-nurses-new-hope"><em>&ldquo;The other students could not believe that people from a rural part of Liberia were going to sit the nursing exam.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Malcom Smith, one of the first public university students in decades to earn a nursing license in Liberia, who was tutored by PIH clinicians &nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<a href="http://www.pih.org/blog/young-boy-overcomes-hodgkin-lymphoma-in-mexico"><em>&ldquo;I only did what I had to do&mdash;fight as much as I could for the life of a child.&rdquo;</em></a><br />
	Dr. Azucena Espinosa, a PIH social service physician working in Chiapas, Mexico, who helped a boy get treatment for and overcome a severe case of&nbsp;Hodgkin Lymphoma&nbsp;</p>
