      <dc:subject></dc:subject>
      <dc:date>2015-12-17T14:56:13+00:00</dc:date>
      <dc:creator></dc:creator>
    </item>
<item>
      <title>Top 10 Books Written by Dr. Paul Farmer</title>
      <link>http://www.pih.org/blog/top-10-books-written-by-dr.-paul-farmer</link>
      <guid>http://www.pih.org/blog/top-10-books-written-by-dr.-paul-farmer</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[<div><figure class="bp-header-photo" style="margin-left:0;width:100%;max-width:600px;"><img title="blog photo" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/booksheader-2.jpg/@mx_600" style="width:100%;max-width:600px;display:block;"><br><small><figcaption></figcaption></small></figure></div><br><p>
	Wondering what to read after <a href="http://amzn.to/1P7ASjH">Tracy Kidder&rsquo;s <em>Mountains Beyond Mountains</em></a>? We&rsquo;ve compiled 10 of what we think are PIH co-founder Dr. Paul Farmer&rsquo;s most powerful books, ordered chronologically, with brief reviews. Written from the perspective of an anthropologist and physician, his works are extensively researched and based on the experiences of the people he has met and treated.</p>
<p>
	All the books offer his greatest selling point (apart from his fondness for alliteration)&mdash;that it&rsquo;s possible to change the world and end the suffering of so many people who are poor.</p>
<p>
	Read during the holiday season, these books offer reasons for hope.</p>
<hr />
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="width:100%;max-width: 650px;">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/aidsandaccusation-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; float: right; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px;" />
				<h3>
					AIDS and Accusation</h3>
				<p>
					While serving Haitian communities as a young doctor, Farmer wrote about the country&rsquo;s HIV epidemic for his doctoral dissertation in anthropology, which later became his first book.</p>
				<p>
					Farmer describes the lives of Haitian villagers and places them in historical context, showing how developments as seemingly unrelated as the building of a dam&nbsp;led them to become victims of <em>sida</em>&nbsp;or&nbsp;AIDS. He aims to erase the stereotypical accusations cast on Haiti&mdash;as source and breeder of the epidemic&mdash;and demonstrate the role poverty and social inequality played in the spread of HIV.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9vX2t?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/infectionsandinequalities-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Infections and Inequalities</h3>
				<p>
					The title might suggest a dense read for the medically minded, but <em>Infections and Inequalities</em> has a clear message: Treatable infectious diseases still plague the world because the people suffering them suffer social inequalities. Farmer tells the stories of patients he treated for HIV and tuberculosis in Haiti and shows what it means to be poor, challenging prevailing ideas of scholars and public health authorities that overlook these causes of illness.</p>
				<p>
					The tale of 19-year-old Robert David on a heroic&nbsp;quest for tuberculosis drugs is one of Farmer&rsquo;s most powerful bits of writing.</p>
				<p>
					In short, the book drives home PIH&rsquo;s message that poverty makes you sick.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9w8e2?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/pathologiesofpower-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Pathologies of Power</h3>
				<p>
					Drawing on his experiences in Haiti, Chiapas, and Russia, <em>Pathologies of Power</em> is Farmer&rsquo;s hard-hitting demonstration of the abused rights of poor people by those in positions of power. It serves as a rallying cry to the world to take action against &ldquo;structural violence&rdquo;&mdash;a phrase Farmer adopted to describe atrocities impoverished people endure that many people simply regard as &ldquo;the way things are.&rdquo; As Nobel Prize-winning economist Amartya Sen writes in the foreword, &ldquo;Paul Farmer teaches us how to stop whistling and start thinking.&rdquo;</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9waCD?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/usesofhaiti-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					The Uses of Haiti</h3>
				<p>
					<em>In The Uses of Haiti</em>, Farmer passionately delivers evidence of the historical ties between the United States and political upheaval in Haiti&mdash;the consequences of which are felt most by the poor. As the title implies, Haiti and its poor are victims of others&rsquo; practices in the country. Farmer does not sugarcoat the link between U.S. foreign policy and the devastation felt by so many of Haiti&rsquo;s people. He points out, for example, that it was a U.S. army school in Georgia, formerly known as the School of the Americas, that formally trained one of Haiti&rsquo;s chiefs of national police in methods of torture.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1P7wscJ?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/partner-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Partner to the Poor</h3>
				<p>
					<em>Partner to the Poor</em> is a 660-page collection of 20 years&rsquo; of some of Farmer&rsquo;s publications. Roughly chronological, the book tracks Farmer&rsquo;s thinking over time. Chapters are organized into four sections, allowing a deeper dive for anyone interested in topics such as his earlier anthropological work on HIV or structural violence and human rights.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9wrWe?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/haiti-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Haiti After the Earthquake</h3>
				<p>
					<em>Haiti After the Earthquake</em> is Farmer&rsquo;s descriptive and moving firsthand account of treating the injured and ill shortly after the country&rsquo;s January 2010 earthquake, and of the cholera epidemic and chaos that ensued long after the rumbles faded. The book, which includes chapters by his friends, family, and colleagues, is an attempt to remember and record the catastrophe, make sense of it, and identify causes that are not just natural. He draws on Haiti&rsquo;s history to show how the country and its capital were vulnerable to the disaster. And he offers lessons learned from messy humanitarian and funding efforts that resulted in more pain to a deeply wounded Haiti.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9wvFs?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/repair-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					To Repair the World</h3>
				<p>
					<em>To Repair the World </em>is a collection of Farmer&rsquo;s commencement speeches meant to guide, inspire, and challenge undergraduate, public health, and medical school students. His humor, indignation, and zeal shine through in stories he shares about the people he has met and the work he has done around the world. His advice includes tips on where all of your most important achievements on this planet will come from, and what the movie <em>The Matrix</em> has to do with the future of medicine. Every page is packed with insight and reflection.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1P7wS2J?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/company-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					In the Company of the Poor</h3>
				<p>
					This slim volume is largely a conversation between Farmer and Father Gustavo Guti&eacute;rrez, an 87-year-old Catholic priest who is regarded as the founder of liberation theology. Farmer first read Guti&eacute;rrez&rsquo;s work as a young doctor in Haiti. Much of the Peruvian priest&rsquo;s writings inspired Farmer&rsquo;s approach to social medicine and have guided PIH&rsquo;s work since. It&rsquo;s a good read for those seeking to understand some of PIH&rsquo;s principles, such as our &ldquo;preferential option for the poor&rdquo; and &ldquo;accompaniment.&rdquo;</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9wSjq?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/reimagining-web.JPG" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Reimagining Global Health</h3>
				<p>
					Written by a number of co-authors, <em>Reimagining Global Health</em> draws from a variety of disciplines, presenting theory, historical evidence, case studies, and frameworks to those interested in understanding global health. Students learn everything from how smallpox was eradicated, to how foreign aid works. Different from a common textbook, the authors make a case for global health as a new field of study. Farmer defines global health as a &ldquo;collection of problems&rdquo; and presents this book as a &ldquo;toolkit&rdquo; for tackling them. His teachings weave throughout and sections are devoted to PIH&rsquo;s work. While its primary goal is to educate, <em>Reimagining Global Health</em> is also a call to action.</p>
				<p style="text-align:left">
					<a class="donate action-light" href="http://amzn.to/1I9x2r2?subsource=TopTenBooks_blogpost" style="">Buy it</a></p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
				<img alt="" src="http://act.pih.org/page/-/images/blog/tk-web.jpg" style="width: 275px; height: 275px; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; float: right;" />
				<h3>
					Coming Soon</h3>
				<p>
					In September 2014, PIH joined the governments of Sierra Leone and Liberia alongside other humanitarian organizations to combat the Ebola epidemic that ultimately killed more than 11,000 people in West Africa. PIH has since committed to stay and help build the health systems in both countries for the long term.</p>
				<p>
					During the height of the epidemic, Farmer treated patients and worked with both ministries of health. He&rsquo;s now writing a book about the crisis, which will be published in 2016.</p>
				<p>
					Stay tuned for a publication date!</p>
				<hr />
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>
<h3>
